{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a535d62f-c160-490b-9aec-18bbb803c8d1","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 adds **first-class span support** with implicit conversions from `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes **overload resolution**: `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, which cannot be represented in expression trees. The expression tree either fails to compile or produces a node the interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) cannot execute.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`, forcing the compiler back to `Enumerable.Contains`:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nOr call the extension method explicitly:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Linq;\n\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth forms bind to `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` — a regular static method with no ref structs — so the expression tree and its interpreter work as before.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"67810415-0435-47f3-a5fa-49e257648ec9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to **extension members** and how the compiler resolves certain method calls. Specifically, C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's been a change in how `Enumerable.Contains()` vs array-specific contains is resolved.\n \nI'm reconsidering the actual mechanism here—it's likely that in .NET 10, the method resolution for `Contains()` on arrays changed, possibly due to new overloads or a shift in how the compiler prioritizes between the array's built-in method and the LINQ extension method.\n\nActually, I think the real culprit is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is now being preferred over `Enumerable.Contains`, especially since C# 14 allows implicit array-to-span conversions. The issue is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` uses `Span<T>` or `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which aren't directly supported in expression trees the same way static method calls are. this static extension method. Both compilation and interpretation work fine.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, implicit span conversions mean `int[]` can convert to `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, so the compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains`. But since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct and can't appear in expression trees, this should fail at compile time—unless the expression tree is being constructed in a way that bypasses those checks.\n\nThe user says it throws at runtime though, which suggests the compiler might still be generating the expression tree (possibly with a warning), but the expression tree interpreter can't handle the ref struct at runtime. Let me reconsider what's actually happening in C# 14 when this lambda gets converted to an expression tree.\n\nI think the key issue is that C# 14 introduced first-class span support, so arrays now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which means method overload resolution picks `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. But expression trees can't represent ref structs, so the interpreter fails when it tries to execute this at runtime. span, T value)` becomes a better match than `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T> source, T value)` for arrays\n\nFor regular lambda expressions (compiled to delegates), this is fine - the span-based version works and is actually faster.\n\nBut for **expression trees** (`Expression<Func<...>>`), this is problematic because:\n- Expression trees cannot contain ref structs (like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`)\n- The compiler should reject this at compile time\n\nSo actually, I think this would be a **compile-time error** in C# 14, not a runtime error. The user might be confused about when the error occurs, or there might be a specific scenario where it's a runtime error.\n\nLet me reconsider: maybe the expression tree compiles fine because the compiler still picks `Enumerable.Contains` for expression tree contexts (it knows about the limitations), but something about how the interpreter handles the method call in .NET 10 is causing issues. Perhaps a new instance method was added to arrays, and the expression tree is now capturing that instead of the extension method, which the interpreter doesn't handle correctly. The issue is that C# 14's implicit span conversions make the compiler optimize `Contains` calls to use `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with `ReadOnlySpan`, but expression trees can't represent ref struct parameters—so the tree either fails to compile or constructs successfully but throws at runtime when the interpreter tries to execute a method signature it can't handle. The user's \"throws at runtime\" suggests the expression tree builds fine but the interpreter chokes when it encounters the span-based method call it can't interpret. When the compiler sees `array.Contains(num)` in a regular (non-expression-tree) context, it now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`. But in an expression tree context, the compiler **should** fall back to `Enumerable.Contains` since span types can't be in expression trees.\n\nHowever, there might be a scenario where:\n1. The compiler correctly identifies this as `MemoryExtensions.Contains` \n2. But then fails to compile the expression tree because it involves ref structs\n3. This would be a **compile-time error**\n\nSo I think the user would actually get a compile-time error like `error CS8640: Expression tree cannot contain value of ref struct type 'ReadOnlySpan<int>'`. But they said \"runtime\" error, which makes me wonder if they're building the expression tree manually or if the C# 14 compiler is somehow producing the expression tree anyway and the error manifests at runtime.\n\nThe real issue is that C# 14's first-class span support changes overload resolution so `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since expression trees can't represent ref struct types like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, this breaks code using `.Contains()` on arrays within expression trees. The fix would be to explicitly cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, or find another way to disambiguate. I'm considering a few other explanations—maybe the expression tree compiles fine but the .NET 10 interpreter has trouble with span operations, or perhaps `Enumerable.Contains` was internally refactored to use spans and the JIT handles it but the interpreter doesn't. Either way, I should just give the technically correct answer about the root cause and mention both the compile-time and runtime possibilities.","outputTokens":3446},"id":"4718f8c5-7271-40fc-9bdd-59fa1eaade08","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:31:01.216Z","parentId":"2a8d6caa-81b7-4874-a542-e75a13b7aa0a"}
